{"title_page": "Avis Crocombe", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Avis Crocombe\n| image              = Avis Crocombe and Benjamin Stride 1886.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = Possible image of Avis Crocombe and husband Benjamin Stride, 1886\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = c. 1839\n| birth_place        = [[Martinhoe]], [[Devon]], England\n| death_date         = 1927 <!-- {{death year and age|1927|1837}} --> (aged 88)<ref>''England & Wales, Civil Registration Death Index, 1916-2007''</ref>\n| death_place        = [[Marylebone]], London, England\n| death_cause        = \n| nationality        = British\n| residence          = London, England\n| education          = \n| alma mater         = \n| occupation         = Cook\n| title              = \n| term               = \n| predecessor        = \n| successor          = \n| known for          = Head cook at Audley End House\n| boards             = \n| salary             = \n| networth           = \n| spouse             = {{marriage|Benjamin Stride|1884}}\n| children           = \n| parents            = \n| relations          = \n| website            = \n}}\n[[File:Audley End Morris edited.jpg|thumb|\"Audley End\" from Morris's ''Country Seats'' (1880)]]\n\n'''Avis Crocombe''' (c. 1839\u20131927) was an English domestic servant who was the head cook during the 1880s at [[Audley End House]], a 17th-century country house near [[Saffron Walden]] in England. She found fame nearly a century after her death thanks to being featured in a series of [[YouTube]] videos featuring her as the main character, cooking recipes from the era. These include a small selection from her own manuscript cookery book. She and other characters from the 1880s are the focus of a long-running live interpretation project at the house, started in 2008 and still ongoing as of 2019.<ref name=\"bbc2018\"/>\n\n==Life==\nAvis Crocombe was born into a large family at [[Martinhoe]], Devon, around 1839<ref>[https://www.familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:MQTF-F4B Avis Crocombe England and Wales Census, 1841.] Family Search. Retrieved 4 October 2018. {{subscription required}}</ref><ref name=1881census>[https://www.familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:QK65-XY6F Avis Crocombe England and Wales Census, 1881.] Family Search. Retrieved 4 October 2018. {{subscription required}}</ref> to Richard Crocombe, a farmer, and Agnes Crocombe.<ref>''1841 England Census''</ref>\n\nAvis entered domestic service before her 13th birthday.<ref name=\"thetimes\"/>  She initially worked for her brother John in Devon, but by 1861 was working as a kitchenmaid for [[John Townshend, 1st Earl Sydney|John Townshend, Viscount Sydney]], one of a staff of at least 10, including a male cook and several footmen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ancestry.co.uk/account/signin?returnurl=https%3a%2f%2fwww.ancestry.co.uk%2finteractive%2f8767%2fMDXRG9_62_64-0265%2f336878%3fbackurl%3dhttps%3a%2f%2fwww.ancestry.co.uk%2ffamily-tree%2fperson%2ftree%2f100624902%2fperson%2f420085227370%2ffacts&secRedir=1|title=Ancestry - Sign In|website=www.ancestry.co.uk|access-date=2018-12-21}}</ref>  By 1871, she was working as a cook and housekeeper in the household of [[Thomas Proctor Beauchamp]] at [[Langley Hall]], Norfolk, one of 16 servants employed by the family.<ref>[https://www.familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:KD89-71Q Avis Crocombe England and Wales Census, 1871.] Family Search. Retrieved 4 October 2018. {{subscription required}}</ref> Sometime before 1881, she became cook to the family of  [[Baron Braybrooke|the 5th Baron Braybrooke]] whose country seat was at [[Audley End House]] near [[Saffron Walden]].<ref name=\"thetimes\"/> As was usual for cooks, she also worked at the family's home in London at [[Upper Brook Street]], and for them in their seaside home at Branksome Towers in Bournemouth.<ref name=1881census/> She replaced a male French chef (a Mons. Merer), but the family were probably cost-cutting, for Avis would have been substantially cheaper. Although staff wages are not known at Audley for 1881, in general male cooks commanded around \u00a3100-120 p.a., (the upper end if French), whereas women's salaries ranged from \u00a340-60. Those who, like Avis, had trained under male cooks could expect higher wages than those who had not.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rachellaudan.com/2016/05/servants-in-the-kitchen-professed-cooks-and-plain-cooks.html|title=Servants in the Kitchen: Professed Cooks and Plain Cooks|last=Laudan|first=Rachel|date=2016-05-09|website=Rachel Laudan|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-21}}</ref>\n\nAvis Crocombe left Audley End in 1884 when she married Benjamin Stride, who ran a lodging house in London. He died in 1893, leaving \u00a3496.6s.8d, and she continued to run the business, along with his daughter (her step-daughter) Anna-Jane.<ref name=\"thetimes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/youtube-gets-a-taste-for-victorian-values-v7rzwrmnp|author=Mark Bridge|title=YouTube gets a taste for Victorian values|website=The Times|accessdate=3 October 2018}} {{subscription required}}</ref><ref>[https://probatesearch.service.gov.uk/Calendar/GetImgSrc?filePath=%2F1893%2FS%2F002124_strevens_1893.Png 1893 Probate Calendar.] Retrieved 4 October 2018.</ref> She died in 1927, aged 89, by now a servant-keeper in her own right.\n\n==Legacy==\nIn 2008, [[English Heritage]], a charity which cares for over 400 monuments and sites across Britain, including Audley End, undertook a multi-million pound restoration of the service wing, funded by the [[Heritage Lottery Fund]]. As part of the interpretation, historical reenactment company Past Pleasures provided costumed characters, who animated the service wing portraying the servants as listed in the 1881 census. The project centred around live cookery, with the team in character, talking to the public and sharing with them recipes from the era. It was initially led by food historian [http://www.anniegray.co.uk Annie Gray], and then by experienced historical interpreter and educator, Kathy Hipperson. Initially, recipes were sourced from books appropriate to the era, but in 2009 Benjamin Stride's descendant Robert Stride bought tickets to see a concert at Audley End. The name sparked a memory, and he realised that he had Avis's hand-written recipe book in a drawer. He donated it to [[English Heritage]], and the costumed team were able to integrate the recipes written by Avis into their work. The book also enabled Gray to work more closely on the sources available to Crocombe, and the style of cookery likely to have been seen at Audley in the 1880s. Crocombe copied several recipes from [[Eliza Acton]]'s ''Modern Cookery for Private Families'' (1845), for example, while others were sourced from newspapers and visitors to the house.<ref name=\"thetimes\" /><ref name=\"cambridge-news\">[https://www.cambridge-news.co.uk/news/cambridge-news/youtube-crocombe-audley-end-victorian-15092098 Meet the YouTube cook going viral - 140 years after her death.] Freddie Lynne, Cambridgeshire Live, 9 September 2018. Retrieved 4 October 2018.</ref>\n\nAvis Crocombe is regularly portrayed as part of the interpretation at the house, and is played by a number of different interpreters.\n\n=== YouTube ===\nEnglish Heritage has commissioned a number of videos for their YouTube channel featuring Kathy Hipperson playing Avis. Coming under the banner of 'The Victorian Way', they are part-demonstration, part-historical showcase, and draw upon recipes from both Avis' book and many others from the period, to both engage and entertain as part of English Heritage's mission, to 'inspire and entertain', with 'authenticity, quality, imagination, responsibility and fun'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/about-us/our-values/|title=Our vision and values|website=English Heritage|access-date=2018-12-21}}</ref> The videos were produced by Gareth Clifford of the Digital Content Team, assisted by Annie Gray, and several English Heritage staff have also appeared, including historian Andrew Hann (whose work on Avis has enabled positive identification of a photograph donated with the recipe book as probably being Avis and Benjamin),<ref>{{Citation|last=English Heritage|title=A Photograph of the Real Mrs Crocombe?|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=j7-TCs9Yj50&vl=en-GB|access-date=2018-12-21}}</ref> and the current curator of Audley End, Peter Moore. In 2018 English Heritage also collaborated with James Townsend & Son, an American costumed interpretation and historic props company, with crossover videos featuring packages sent from the UK to the US and vice versa.\n\nThe Victorian Way videos had received over 12 million views as of August 2018.<ref name=\"bbc2018\">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-england-essex-45360643/victorian-cook-s-1880s-recipes-inspire-millions-online Victorian cook's 1880s recipes inspire millions online.] BBC News, 30 August 2018. Retrieved 4 October 2018.</ref> In June 2019 English Heritage won both Breakthrough Advertiser and the Grand Prix awards at the [[YouTube]] Works (UK) awards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://youtube.thinkwithgoogle.com/youtube-works#grand-prix-breakthrough-advertiser-english-heritage|title=YouTube Works - Think With Google|website=youtube.thinkwithgoogle.com|access-date=2019-06-17}}</ref> In late 2019 a tie-in book was announced with recipes and history<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.english-heritageshop.org.uk/books-media/how-to-cook-the-victorian-way-with-mrs-crocombe|title=Buy How To Cook The Victorian Way With Mrs Crocombe {{!}} English Heritage|website=www.english-heritageshop.org.uk|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref>. \n[[File:Youtubeworksenglishheritage.jpg|thumb|The English Heritage content marketing team, together with Kathy Hipperson and Annie Gray, at the YouTube Works award ceremony, June 2019]]\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Audley End House & Gardens (EH) 06-05-2012 (7710677416).jpg|Kathy Hipperson playing Avis Crocombe\nFile:Audley End House & Gardens (EH) 06-05-2012 (7710680614).jpg|Kathy Hipperson and assistant\nFile:Audley End House & Gardens (EH) 06-05-2012 (7710682888).jpg|Kitchens at Audley End House seen in 2012\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Audley End House}}\n{{commons category}}\n* The full [https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLx2QMoA1Th9deXXbo7htq21CUPqEPPGuc Victorian Way] playlist on the English Heritage YouTube channel\n*The [https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/visit/places/audley-end-house-and-gardens/things-to-do/the-service-wing2/ Service Wing] page at the Audley End website, including link to event days when the costumed team can be seen on site.\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crocombe, Avis}}\n[[Category:People from North Devon (district)]]\n[[Category:English domestic workers]]\n[[Category:Hoteliers]]\n[[Category:English chefs]]\n[[Category:Women chefs]]\n[[Category:19th-century British women]]\n[[Category:20th-century British women]]\n[[Category:1830s births]]\n[[Category:1927 deaths]]\n[[Category:Year of birth uncertain]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Avis Crocombe\n| image              = Avis Crocombe and Benjamin Stride 1886.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = Possible image of Avis Crocombe and husband Benjamin Stride, 1886\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = c. 1839\n| birth_place        = [[Martinhoe]], [[Devon]], England\n| death_date         = 1927 <!-- {{death year and age|1927|1837}} --> (aged 88)<ref>''England & Wales, Civil Registration Death Index, 1916-2007''</ref>\n| death_place        = [[Marylebone]], London, England\n| death_cause        = \n| nationality        = British\n| residence          = London, England\n| education          = \n| alma mater         = \n| occupation         = Cook\n| title              = \n| term               = \n| predecessor        = \n| successor          = \n| known for          = Head cook at Audley End House\n| boards             = \n| salary             = \n| networth           = \n| spouse             = {{marriage|Benjamin Stride|1884}}\n| children           = \n| parents            = \n| relations          = \n| website            = \n}}\n[[File:Audley End Morris edited.jpg|thumb|\"Audley End\" from Morris's ''Country Seats'' (1880)]]\n\n'''Avis Crocombe''' (c. 1839\u20131927) was an English domestic servant who was the head cook during the 1880s at [[Audley End House]], a 17th-century country house near [[Saffron Walden]] in England. She found fame nearly a century after her death thanks to being featured in a series of [[YouTube]] videos featuring her as the main character, cooking recipes from the era. These include a small selection from her own manuscript cookery book. She and other characters from the 1880s are the focus of a long-running live interpretation project at the house, started in 2008 and still ongoing as of 2019.<ref name=\"bbc2018\"/>\n\n==Life==\nAvis Crocombe was born into a large family at [[Martinhoe]], Devon, around 1839<ref>[https://www.familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:MQTF-F4B Avis Crocombe England and Wales Census, 1841.] Family Search. Retrieved 4 October 2018. {{subscription required}}</ref><ref name=1881census>[https://www.familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:QK65-XY6F Avis Crocombe England and Wales Census, 1881.] Family Search. Retrieved 4 October 2018. {{subscription required}}</ref> to Richard Crocombe, a farmer, and Agnes Crocombe.<ref>''1841 England Census''</ref>\n\nAvis entered domestic service before her 13th birthday.<ref name=\"thetimes\"/>  She initially worked for her brother John in Devon, but by 1861 was working as a kitchenmaid for [[John Townshend, 1st Earl Sydney|John Townshend, Viscount Sydney]], one of a staff of at least 10, including a male cook and several footmen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ancestry.co.uk/account/signin?returnurl=https%3a%2f%2fwww.ancestry.co.uk%2finteractive%2f8767%2fMDXRG9_62_64-0265%2f336878%3f