{"title_page": "Crime in India", "text_new": "Murder district in the world\n\n==Crime over time==\n[[File:Crime in India from 1953 to 2007.png|thumb|500px|right|alt=India Is Criminal Justice Law System. Crime in India from 1953 to 2007|Incidence of cognisable crimes in India 1953\u20132007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ncrb.nic.in/cii2007/cii-2007/1953-2007.pdf|title=Incidence of cognizable crimes (IPC) under different crime heads during 1953\u20132007|publisher=National Crime Records Bureau|accessdate=2009-11-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090619063832/http://ncrb.nic.in/CII2007/cii-2007/1953-2007.pdf|archive-date=19 June 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n]]\nA report published by the [[National Crime Records Bureau]] compared the crime rates of 1953 and 2006. The report noted that burglary (known as house-breaking<ref name=kanoon>{{cite web|title=Central Government Act Section 445 in The Indian Penal Code|url=http://indiankanoon.org/doc/508356/|website=Indiankanoon.org|accessdate=16 July 2015}}</ref> in India) declined over a period of 53 years by 79.84% (from 147,379, a rate of 39.3/100,000 in 1953 to 91,666, a rate of 7.9/100,000 in 2006), murder has increased by 7.39% (from 9,803, a rate of 2.61 in 1953 to 32,481, a rate of 2.81/100,000 in 2006).<ref name=\"NCRBSNAPSHOTS1953-2006\">[http://ncrb.nic.in/cii2006/cii-2006/Snapshots%201953-2006.pdf Snapshots (1953\u20142006)]{{Dead link|date=November 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} ''National Crime Records Bureau''</ref>\n\n[[Kidnapping]] has increased by 47.80% (from 5,261, a rate of 1.40/100,000 in 1953 to 23,991, a rate of 2.07/100,000 in 2006), robbery has declined by 28.85% (from 8,407, rate of 2.24/100,000 in 1953 to 18,456, rate of 1.59/100,000 in 2006) and [[riots]] have declined by 10.58% (from 20,529, a rate of 5.47/100,000 in 1953 to 56,641, a rate of 4.90/100,000 in 2006).<ref name=\"NCRBSNAPSHOTS1953-2006\"/>\n\nIn 2006, {{formatnum:5102460}} cognisable crimes were committed including {{formatnum:1878293}} [[Indian Penal Code]] (IPC) crimes and {{formatnum:3224167}} Special & Local Laws (SLL) crimes, with an increase of 1.5% over 2005 (50,26,337).<ref name=NCRBSNAPSHOTS2006/> IPC crime rate in 2006 was 167.7 compared to 165.3 in 2005 showing an increase of 1.5% in 2006 over 2005.<ref name=NCRBSNAPSHOTS2006/> SLL crime rate in 2006 was 287.9 compared to 290.5 in 2005 showing a decline of 0.9% in 2006 over 2005.<ref name=NCRBSNAPSHOTS2006/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; margin-right:60px\"\n!Year<ref name=\"NCRBSNAPSHOTS1953-2006\"/>\n!Total cog. crimes under IPC, per 100,000\n!Murder per 100,000\n!Kidnapping per 100,000\n!Robbery per 100,000\n!Burglary (known as house-breaking in India) per 100,000\n|-\n|'''1953'''||160.5||2.61||1.40||2.24||39.3||\n|-\n|'''2006'''||162.3||2.81||2.07||1.60||7.92||\n|-\n|'''% Change in 2006 over 1953'''||1.1||7.39||47.80||-28.85||-79.84||\n|}\n\n'''SOURCE: National Crime Records Bureau<ref name=\"NCRBSNAPSHOTS1953-2006\"/>'''\n\n==Crime by location==\nLocation has a significant impact on crime in India. In 2012, [[Uttar Pradesh]] reported the highest cognisable crime rate of 455.8 among [[States and territories of India|States]] of [[India]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ncrb.nic.in/CD-CII2012/Statistics2012.pdf |title=Crime in India, 2012 |publisher=NCRB, Government of India |page=200 |year=2012 |accessdate=April 20, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140620023952/http://ncrb.nic.in/CD-CII2012/Statistics2012.pdf |archivedate=20 June 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/crime-rate-highest-in-kerala/article4822947.ece | title=Crime rate highest in Kerala | newspaper=The Hindu | accessdate=April 20, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Kerala-is-countrys-most-crime-prone-state-NCRB-statistics-show/articleshow/14364473.cms | title=Kerala is country's most crime-prone state, NCRB statistics show | newspaper=Times of India | accessdate=April 20, 2014}}</ref> while [[Nagaland]] recorded lowest rates (47.7). The rates were calculated by [[National Crime Records Bureau]] as the number of incidents per 100,000 of the population.\n\nIn 2006, the highest crime rate was reported in [[Puducherry]] (447.7) for crimes under [[Indian Penal Code]] which is 2.7 times the national crime rate of 167.7.<ref name=NCRBSNAPSHOTS2006/> [[Kerala]] reported the highest crime rate at 312.5 amongst all the states of India.<ref name=NCRBSNAPSHOTS2006/> \n[[Kolkata]] (71.0) the only mega city and [[Madurai]] (206.2) were the only Metropolis which reported less crime rate than their domain states [[West Bengal]] (79.0) and [[Tamil Nadu]] (227.6).<ref name=NCRBSNAPSHOTS2006/> [[Delhi]], [[Mumbai]] and [[Bangalore]] have accounted for 16.2%, 9.5% and 8.1% respectively of the total IPC crimes reported from 35 mega cities.<ref name=NCRBSNAPSHOTS2006/> [[Indore]] reported the highest crime rate (769.1) among the mega cities in India followed by [[Bhopal]] (719.5) and [[Jaipur]] (597.1).<ref name=NCRBSNAPSHOTS2006/>\n\n[[Jammu and Kashmir]] (33.7%), [[Manipur]] (33.0%), [[Assam]] (30.4%) and [[Daman and Diu]] and [[Puducherry]] (29.4%) reported higher violent crime rate compared to 18.4% at national level.<ref name=NCRBSNAPSHOTS2006/> [[Uttar Pradesh]] reported the highest incidence of violent crimes accounting for 12.1% of total violent crimes in India (40,613 out of 3,305,901) followed by [[Maharashtra]] with 11.1% (30,290 out of 3,305,901).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ncrb.gov.in/StatPublications/CII/CII2015/FILES/Snapshots-11.11.16.pdf |title=Snapshots 2015|work=[[National Crime Records Bureau]] |accessdate=18 December 2016}}</ref> Among 35 mega cities, [[Delhi]] reported 31.2% (533 out of 1,706) of total rape cases.<ref name=NCRBSNAPSHOTS2006/> [[Madhya Pradesh]] has reported the highest number of rape cases (2,900) accounting for 15.0%  of total such cases reported in the country.<ref name=NCRBSNAPSHOTS2006/> Uttar Pradesh reported 10% (5,480 out of 32,481) of total murder cases in the country and 18.4% (4,997 out of 27,230)    total attempt to murder cases.<ref name=NCRBSNAPSHOTS2006/>\n\n{{Asof|2016}} [[Uttar Pradesh]] had a lower crime rate when solely considering crimes punished under the IPC, but because of the large number of offences being prosecuted under its local laws and special laws, its overall crime rate, 1,293, is ten times the size of its IPC crime rate.<ref>{{cite news|author=Tiwary, Deepman|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/explained/ncrb-data-uttar-pradesh-crime-rate-up-police-3033360/|title=NCRB data: The odd case of crime in Uttar Pradesh, IPC rate very low, overall very high|newspaper=[[Indian Express]]|date=2016-09-26|accessdate=2017-02-14}}</ref>{{irrelevant citation|date=July 2017|reason=Opinion based, irrelevant article referenced.}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! State/UT !! 2011 !! 2012\n|-\n|India || || 2.8\n|-\n|[[Bihar]]  || 3.3 || 3.2\n|-\n| [[Arunachal Pradesh]] || 4.7 || 5.8\n|-\n| [[Assam]] || 4.2 || 4.4\n|-\n| [[Andhra Pradesh]] || 3.1 || 3.6\n|-\n| [[Chhattisgarh]] || 4.3 || 4.0\n|-\n| [[Goa]] || 3.3 || 2.5\n|-\n| [[Gujarat]] || 1.9 || 1.9\n|-\n| [[Haryana]] || 4.2 || 3.8\n|-\n| [[Himachal Pradesh]] || 1.9 || 1.6\n|-\n| [[Jammu & Kashmir]] || 1.3 || 1.0\n|-\n| [[Jharkhand]]|| 5.3 || 5.3\n|-\n| [[Karnataka]] || 3.0 || 3.1\n|-\n| [[Delhi]] || 1.1 || 1.1\n|-\n| [[Madhya Pradesh]] || 3.5 || 3.2\n|-\n| [[Maharashtra]] || 2.5 || 2.4\n|-\n| [[Manipur]] || 2.9 || 3.3\n|-\n| [[Meghalaya]] || 2.9 || 5.1\n|-\n| [[Mizoram]] || 2.4 || 2.9\n|-\n| [[Nagaland]] || 2.3 || 3.3\n|-\n| [[Odisha]] || 3.5 || 3.8\n|-\n| [[Punjab, India|Punjab]] || 3.0 || 3.0\n|-\n| [[Rajasthan]] || 2.1 || 2.1\n|-\n| [[Sikkim]] || 2.3 || 1.1\n|-\n| [[Tamil Nadu]] || 2.6 || 2.9\n|-\n| [[Tripura]] || 4.4 || 3.4\n|-\n| [[Uttar Pradesh]] || 7.5 || 7.4\n|-\n| [[Uttarakhand]] || 1.8 || 2.1\n|-\n| [[West Bengal]]  || 2.3 || 2.5\n|-\n| [[Kerala]] || 10 || 5\n\n|}\n\nSources.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ncrb.nic.in/CD-CII2011/cii-2011/Table%203.1.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-09-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130928024506/http://ncrb.nic.in/CD-CII2011/cii-2011/Table%203.1.pdf |archivedate=28 September 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>[[List of states and union territories of India by population]]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ncrb.nic.in/CD-CII2012/Statistics2012.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=20 April 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140620023952/http://ncrb.nic.in/CD-CII2012/Statistics2012.pdf |archivedate=20 June 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Crimes against women==\n{{Main|Violence against women in India}}\n\nPolice records shows incidence of crimes against women in India.<ref name=\"un_women_free_equal\">{{cite web\n |title=Women in India: How Free? How Equal? \n |url=http://www.un.org.in/wii.htm \n |author=Kalyani Menon-Sen, [[A. K. Shiva Kumar]] \n |publisher=United Nations \n |year=2001 \n |accessdate=2006-12-24 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060911183722/http://www.un.org.in/wii.htm \n |archivedate=11 September 2006 \n |url-status=dead \n |df=dmy \n}}</ref> Sexual assault against women in India though not common is present. Despite a large population statistically sexual assault in India is not rampant. Media is active in highlighting cases of Sexual assault against women.<ref name=\"un_women_free_equal\"/>\n\n===Rape===\n{{Main|Rape in India}}\nRape in India has been described by [[Radha Kumar]] as one of India's most common crimes against women.<ref name=Kumar>{{cite book|last=Kumar|first=Radha|title=The History of Doing: An Account of Women's Rights and Feminism in India|year=1993|publisher=Zubaan|isbn=978-8185107769|page=128}}</ref> Official sources show that rape cases in India have doubled between 1990 and 2008<ref name=AFP>{{cite web|title=www.arabnews.com/indian-student-gang-raped-thrown-bus-new-delhi|publisher=AFP|date=17 December 2012}}</ref> In most of the rape cases, the culprit is known to the victim.\n\nAccording to [[National Crime Records Bureau]] data of 2012,<ref name=\"Crime2012\">{{cite web|url=http://ncrb.nic.in/CD-CII2012/Statistics2012.pdf |title=Crime in India, 2012 |publisher=NCRB, Government of India |page=206 |year=2012 |accessdate=April 20, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140620023952/http://ncrb.nic.in/CD-CII2012/Statistics2012.pdf |archivedate=20 June 2014 }}</ref> [[Gujarat]] has the lowest rape rate (0.8) while [[Mizoram]] had the highest rape rate with a value of 10.1. the National Average was at 2.1. The rates were calculated by [[National Crime Records Bureau]] as the number of incidents per 100,000 of the population\n\n===Dowry===\n{{Main|Dowry system in India}}\n\n[[Dowries]] are considered a major contributor towards [[violence against women in India]].  Some of these offences include physical violence, emotional abuses, and murder of brides and girls.<ref name=\"srinivasan 2004\">{{cite journal|last=Srinivasan|first=Padma|author2=Gary R. Lee|title=The Dowry System in Northern India: Women's Attitudes and Social Change|journal=Journal of Marriage and Family|year=2004|volume=66|issue=5|pages=1108\u20131117|doi=10.1111/j.0022-2445.2004.00081.x}}</ref><ref name=\"Teays 1991\">{{cite journal|last=Teays|first=Wanda|title=The Burning Bride: The Dowry Problem in India|journal=Journal of Feminist Studies in Religion|year=1991|volume=7|issue=2|pages=29\u201352}}</ref><ref name=\"Bloch 2002\">{{cite journal|last=Bloch|first=Francis|author2=Vijayendra Rao|title=Terror as a Bargaining Instrument: A Case Study of Dowry Violence in Rural India|journal=The American Economic Review|year=2002|volume=92|issue=4|pages=1029\u20131043|doi=10.1257/00028280260344588|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/beeabaff4f09cafdc47e08adb378db3f360bec10}}</ref>\n\nMost dowry deaths occur when the young woman, unable to bear the harassment and torture, commits suicide. Most of these suicides are by hanging, poisoning or by fire. Sometimes the woman is killed by setting her on fire - this is known as [[bride burning]], and is sometimes disguised as suicide or accident.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Kumar|first=Virendra|title=Burnt wives|journal=Burns|date=Feb 2003|volume=29|issue=1|pages=31\u201336|doi=10.1016/s0305-4179(02)00235-8|pmid=12543042}}</ref> In 2012, 8,233 dowry death cases were reported across India.<ref name=india>{{cite web|url=http://ncrb.nic.in/CD-CII2012/Statistics2012.pdf |title=National Crime Statistics (page 196) |publisher=National Crime Records Bureau, India |date=2013-01-16 |accessdate=2015-01-02 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140620023952/http://ncrb.nic.in/CD-CII2012/Statistics2012.pdf |archivedate=20 June 2014 }}</ref> Dowry issues caused 1.4 deaths per year per 100,000 women in India.<ref>[http://censusindia.gov.in/2011census/censusinfodashboard/index.html Provisional 2011 Census Data], Government of India (2011)</ref><ref name=crimeindia2011>[http://ncrb.nic.in/CD-CII2011/Statistics2011.pdf Crime statistics in India] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130129164006/http://ncrb.nic.in/CD-CII2011/Statistics2011.pdf |date=29 January 2013 }}, Government of India (2011)</ref>\n\n===Domestic violence===\n{{Further|Domestic violence in India}}\n\n[[Domestic violence in India]] is endemic.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Ganguly|first=Sumit|title=India's Shame|url=http://the-diplomat.com/indian-decade/2012/04/14/india%E2%80%99s-shame/|magazine=The Diplomat|accessdate=27 April 2012}}</ref> Around 70% of women in India are victims of domestic violence, according to [[Renuka Chowdhury]], former Union minister for Women and Child Development.<ref name=\"Chowdhury 2006\">{{cite news|last=Chowdhury|first=Renuka|title=India tackles domestic violence|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/6086334.stm|newspaper=BBC|date=26 October 2006}}</ref>\n\nThe National Crime Records Bureau reveal that a crime against a woman is committed every three minutes, a woman is raped every 29 minutes, a [[dowry]] death occurs every 77 minutes, and one case of cruelty committed by either the husband or relative of the husband occurs every nine minutes.<ref name=\"bbctackle\"/> This occurs despite the fact that women in India are legally protected from domestic abuse under the [[Protection of Women from Domestic Violence Act 2005|Protection of Women from Domestic Violence Act]].<ref name=\"bbctackle\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/6086334.stm|title=India tackles domestic violence|date=2006-10-27|work=BBC News|accessdate=25 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Organised crime ==\n{{Further|Organised crime in India}}\n\n===Illegal drug trade===\nIndia is located between two major illicit [[opium]] producing centres in Asia \u2013 the [[Golden Crescent]] comprising [[Pakistan]], [[Afghanistan]] and [[Iran]] and the [[Golden Triangle (Southeast Asia)|Golden Triangle]] comprising [[Burma]], Thailand and [[Laos]].<ref name=\"PINM658\">{{cite book\n|author= P. J. Alexander\n|title= Policing India in the New Millennium\n|publisher= Allied Publishers\n|location=\n|year= 2002\n|pages= 658\n|isbn= 81-7764-207-3\n|oclc=\n|doi=\n}}</ref> Because of such geographical location, India experiences large amount of drug trafficking through the borders.<ref name=\"IDPTU183\">{{cite book\n|author1=Caterina Gouvis Roman |author2=Heather Ahn-Redding |author3=Rita James Simon |title= Illicit Drug Policies, Trafficking, and Use the World Over\n|publisher= Lexington Books\n|location=\n|year= 2007\n|pages= 183\n|isbn= 978-0-7391-2088-0\n|oclc=\n|doi=\n}}</ref> India is the world's largest producer of licit opium for the pharmaceutical trade.<ref name=\" CIA World Factbook\">{{cite web |title=CIA World Factbook \u2013 India|work=[[CIA World Factbook]]|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/in.html |accessdate=2007-12-01}}</ref> But an undetermined quantity of opium is diverted to illicit international drug markets.<ref name=\" CIA World Factbook\"/>\n\nIndia is a transshipment point for heroin from [[Southwest Asian]] countries like [[Afghanistan]] and [[Pakistan]] and from Southeast Asian countries like Burma, Laos, and Thailand.<ref name=SDSU>{{cite web|url=http://www-rohan.sdsu.edu/faculty/rwinslow/asia_pacific/india.html|title=Comparative Criminology - Asia - India|publisher=}}</ref> Heroin is smuggled from [[Pakistan]] and Burma, with some quantities transshipped through Nepal.<ref name=SDSU/> Most heroin shipped from India are destined for Europe.<ref name=SDSU/> There have been reports of heroin smuggled from [[Mumbai]] to [[Nigeria]] for further export.<ref name=SDSU/>\n\nIn [[Maharashtra]], [[Mumbai]] is an important centre for distribution of drug.<ref name=\" Molly Charles\">{{cite web |title=Drug trade dynamics in India|url=http://laniel.free.fr/INDEXES/PapersIndex/INDIAMOLLY/DRUGSDYNAMICSININDIA.htm}}</ref> The most commonly used drug in Mumbai is Indian heroin (called ''desi mal'' by the local population).<ref name=\" Molly Charles\"/> Both public transportation (road and rail transportation) and private transportation are used for this drug trade.<ref name=\" Molly Charles\"/>\n\nDrug trafficking affects the country in many ways.\n*[[Drug abuse]]: Cultivation of illicit narcotic substances and drug trafficking affects the health of the individuals and destroy the economic structure of the family and society.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thishour.in/112/if-you-think-drugs-will-make-you-high-watch-this|title=Life of Drug Addicts: Curtains Down|last=|first=|date=|website=www.thishour.in|publisher=THISHOUR.in|access-date=2016-10-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160918221439/http://www.thishour.in/112/if-you-think-drugs-will-make-you-high-watch-this|archive-date=18 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"PINM659\">{{cite book\n|author= P. J. Alexander\n|title= Policing India in the New Millennium\n|publisher= Allied Publishers\n|location=\n|year= 2002\n|pages= 659\n|isbn= 81-7764-207-3\n|oclc=\n|doi=\n}}</ref>\n*[[Organised crime]]: Drug trafficking results in growth of organised crime which affects [[social security]]. Organised crime connects drug trafficking with corruption and [[money laundering]].<ref name=\"PINM659\"/>\n*Political instability: Drug trafficking also aggravates the political instability in [[North-West India|North-West]] and [[North-East India]].<ref name=\"WGD53\">{{cite book\n|author1=Alain Labrousse |author2=Laurent Laniel |title= The World Geopolitics of Drugs, 1998/1999\n|publisher= Springer\n|location=\n|year= 2002\n|pages= 53\n|isbn= 1-4020-0140-1\n|oclc=\n|doi=\n}}</ref>\n\nA survey conducted in 2003\u20132004 by Narcotics Control Bureau found that India has at least four million drug addicts.<ref name=\" NCB\">{{cite web|title=Mechanism in States|url=http://narcoticsindia.nic.in/Mechinstates.htm}}</ref> The most common drugs used in India are [[Cannabis (drug)|cannabis]], [[hashish]], [[opium]] and heroin.<ref name=\" NCB\"/> In 2006 alone, India's law enforcing agencies recovered 230&nbsp;kg heroin and 203&nbsp;kg of [[cocaine]].<ref name=TOIAIRPORT>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/1680312.cms Airports get scanners to check drug trafficking]</ref> In an annual government report in 2007, the United States named India among 20 major hubs for trafficking of illegal drugs along with Pakistan, Afghanistan and Burma. However, studies reveal that most of the criminals caught in this crime are either Nigerian or [[United States|US]] nationals.<ref name=\" Hindustan\">{{cite web |title=US names India among 20 major hubs for drug trafficking|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/StoryPage/StoryPage.aspx?id=5f7ed0c7-60a5-40fc-bbf1-7e9b4c070f59&&Headline=India+among+20+major+drug+hubs%3a+US}}</ref>\n\nSeveral measures have been taken by the [[Government of India]] to combat drug trafficking in the country. India is a party of the [[Single Convention on Narcotic Drugs]] (1961), the [[Convention on Psychotropic Substances]] (1971), the [[Protocol Amending the Single Convention on Narcotic Drugs]] (1972) and the [[United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances]] (1988).<ref name=\"IPCAWP172\">{{cite book\n|author= Daniel J. Koenig\n|title= International Police Cooperation: A World Perspective\n|publisher= Lexington Books\n|location=\n|year= 2001\n|pages= 172\n|isbn= 0-7391-0226-5\n|oclc=\n|doi=\n}}</ref> An Indo-Pakistani committee was set up in 1986 to prevent trafficking in narcotic drugs.<ref name=\"IPCAWP173\">{{cite book\n|author= Daniel J. Koenig\n|title= International Police Cooperation: A World Perspective\n|publisher= Lexington Books\n|location=\n|year= 2001\n|pages= 173\n|isbn= 0-7391-0226-5\n|oclc=\n|doi=\n}}</ref> India signed a convention with the [[United Arab Emirates]] in 1994 to control drug trafficking.<ref name=\"IPCAWP173\"/> In 1995, India signed an agreement with [[Egypt]] for investigation of drug cases and exchange of information and a [[Memorandum of understanding|Memorandum of Understanding]] of the Prevention of Illicit Trafficking in Drugs with [[Iran]].<ref name=\"IPCAWP173\"/>\n\n===Arms trafficking===\nAccording to a joint report published by [[Oxfam]], [[Amnesty International]] and the [[IANSA (NGO)|International Action Network on Small Arms]] (IANSA) in 2006, there are around 40 million illegal small arms in India out of approximately 75 million in worldwide circulation.<ref name=DTILLEGALARMS>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2006%5C04%5C02%5Cstory_2-4-2006_pg7_11|title=DailyTimes - Your Right To Know|work=DAILYTIMES}}</ref> Majority of the illegal small arms make its way into the states of [[Bihar]], [[Chhattisgarh]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], Jharkhand, [[Orissa, India|Orissa]] and [[Madhya Pradesh]].<ref name=DTILLEGALARMS/> In UP, a used [[AK-47]] costs $3,800 in black market.<ref name=\"HAVOCSCOPE\">{{cite web |title=Small Arms Trafficking|url=http://www.havocscope.com/trafficking/smallarms.htm}}</ref> Large amount of illegal small arms are manufactured in various illegal arms factories in Uttar Pradesh and Bihar and sold on the black market for as little as $5.08.<ref name=DTILLEGALARMS/>\n\nChinese pistols are in demand in the illegal small arms market in India because they are easily available and cheaper.<ref name=DTILLEGALARMS/> This trend poses a significant problem for the states of [[Bihar]], Uttar Pradesh, Jharkhand, Chhattisgarh, Orissa, Maharashtra, [[West Bengal]], Karnataka and [[Andhra Pradesh]] which have influence of [[Naxalism]].<ref name=DTILLEGALARMS/> The porous Indo-Nepal border is an entry point for Chinese pistols, AK-47 and [[M16 rifle|M-16 rifles]] into India as these arms are used by the Naxalites who have ties to Maoists in Nepal.<ref name=DTILLEGALARMS/>\n\nIn [[North-East India]], there is a huge influx of small arms due to the insurgent groups operating there.<ref name=GWDDSA>[http://www.peacebuild.ca/action/res/Bina%20Nepram%20lecture,%2022%20March,%202004,%20Ottawa.doc A Narrative of Armed Ethnic Conflict, Narcotics and Small Arms Trafficking in India's North East]</ref> The small arms in North-East India come from insurgent groups in Burma, black markets in [[Southeast Asia]], [[Pakistan]], Bangladesh, [[Nepal]] and [[Sri Lanka]], black market in [[Cambodia]], the People's Republic of China, insurgent groups like the [[Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam]], the [[Communist Party of India (Maoist)]], the [[Communist Party of Nepal (Maoist)]], Indian states like [[Uttar Pradesh]] and pilferages from legal gun factories,\ncriminal organisations operating in India and South Asian countries and\nother international markets like [[Romania]], Germany etc.<ref name=GWDDSA/> Illegal weaponry found in North-East India includes small arms such as the [[M14 rifle|M14]], [[M16 rifle|M16]], [[AK-47]], [[AK-56]], and the [[AK-74]], but also [[light machine gun]]s, Chinese [[hand grenade]]s, [[Land mine|mines]], [[rocket-propelled grenade|rocket-propelled grenade launchers]] and [[submachine gun]]s etc.<ref name=GWDDSA/>\n\nThe [[Ministry of External Affairs (India)|Ministry of External Affairs]] and [[Ministry of Home Affairs (India)|Ministry of Home Affairs]] drafted a joint proposal to the United Nations, seeking a global ban on small-arms sales to non-state users.<ref name=DTILLEGALARMS/>\n\n==Poaching and wildlife trafficking==\nIllegal wildlife trade in India has increased.<ref name=REUTERSPOACHING>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/environmentNews/idUSDEL8332720070817?sp=true|title=Illegal wildlife trade grows in India|author=Reuters Editorial|date=17 August 2007|work=Reuters}}</ref> According to a report published by the [[Environmental Investigation Agency]] (EIA) in 2004, India is the chief target for the traders of wildlife skin.<ref name=EIATTST>[http://www.eia-international.org/files/reports85-1.pdf The Tiger Skin Trail] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012162946/http://www.eia-international.org/files/reports85-1.pdf |date=12 October 2007 }}</ref> Between 1994 and 2003, there have been 784 cases where the skins of tiger, leopard or [[otter]] have been seized.<ref name=EIATTST/> [[Leopard]]s, [[rhinoceros]], [[reptile]]s, birds, insects, rare species of plants are being smuggled into the countries in Southeast Asia and the People's Republic of China.<ref name=REUTERSPOACHING/> Between 1994 and 2003, poaching and seizure of 698 otters have been documented in India.<ref name=EIATTST/>\n\n[[Kathmandu]] is a key staging point for illegal skins smuggled from India bound for [[Tibet]] and PRC.<ref name=EIATTST/> The report by EIA noted there has been a lack of cross-border cooperation between India, [[Nepal]] and the People's Republic of [[China]] to coordinate enforcement operations and lack of political will to treat wildlife crime effectively.<ref name=EIATTST/> The poaching of the [[Asian Elephant|elephants]] is a significant problem in Southern India<ref name=\"AEEM210\">{{cite book\n|author= R. Sukumar\n|title= The Asian Elephant: Ecology and Management\n|publisher= Cambridge University Press\n|location=\n|year= 1989\n|pages= 210\n|isbn= 0-521-43758-X\n|oclc=\n|doi=\n}}</ref> and in the North-Eastern states of [[Nagaland]] and [[Mizoram]].<ref name=\"AEC30\">{{cite book\n|author1=Charles Santiapillai |author2=Peter Jackson |title= The Asian Elephant: An Action Plan for Its Conservation\n|publisher=\n|location=\n|year= 1990\n|pages= 30\n|isbn= 2-88032-997-3\n|oclc=\n|doi=\n}}</ref> The majority of tiger poaching happen in [[Madhya Pradesh]], Uttar Pradesh, [[Orissa, India|Orissa]], West Bengal, [[Assam]] and [[Arunachal Pradesh]].<ref name=IYT>[http://www.internatyearofthetiger.org/india.htm The situation in India]</ref> Following is a comparison of reported cases of tiger and leopard poaching from 1998 to 2003:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; margin-right:60px\"\n!Year\n!1998\n!1999\n!2000\n!2001\n!2002\n!2003\n|-\n|'''Reported cases of tiger poaching<ref name=PTPS>[http://projecttiger.nic.in/poaching.asp# Poaching & Seizure Cases]</ref>'''||14||38||39||35||47||8\n|-\n|'''Reported cases of leopard poaching<ref name=PTPS/>'''||28||80||201||69||87||15\n|}\n\nSamir Sinha, head of [[Traffic (conservation programme)|TRAFFIC India]], the wildlife trade monitoring arm of the [[World Wide Fund for Nature]] (WWF) and the [[World Conservation Union]] (IUCN), told [[Reuters]] in an interview \"The situation regarding the illegal trade in wildlife parts in India is very grim. It is a vast, a varied trade ranging from smuggling of rare medicinal plants to butterflies to peafowl to tigers and it is difficult to predict how big it is, but the threats and dimensions suggest that the trade is increasing\".<ref name=REUTERSPOACHING/>\n\n[[Project Tiger]], a wildlife conservation project, was initiated in 1972 and was launched by [[Indira Gandhi]] on 1 April 1973.<ref name=REDIFFTIGER>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/1998/oct/02tiger.htm|title=Rediff On The NeT Special: At least one tiger is killed by poachers every day|publisher=}}</ref> With 23 tiger reserves, Project Tiger claimed to have succeeded.<ref name=REDIFFTIGER/> But according to critics like conservationist Billy Arjan Singh, temporary increases in tiger population were caused by immigration due to destruction of habitat in Nepal, not because of the widely acclaimed success of wildlife policy in India.<ref name=REDIFFTIGER/>\n\n==Cyber crime==\n{{Main|Cybercrime in India}}\nThe Information Technology Act 2000 was passed by the [[Parliament of India]] in May 2000, aiming to curb cyber crimes and provide a legal framework for [[Electronic commerce|e-commerce]] transactions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/978231.stm|title=BBC News - SOUTH ASIA - India cyber law comes into force|publisher=}}</ref> However Pavan Duggal, lawyer of [[Supreme Court of India]] and cyber law expert, viewed \"The IT Act, 2000, is primarily meant to be a legislation to promote e-commerce. It is not very effective in dealing with several emerging cyber crimes like [[cyber harassment]], [[defamation]], stalking and so on\". Although cyber crime cells have been set up in major cities, Duggal noted the problem is that most cases remain unreported due to a lack of awareness.<ref name=REDIFFBB>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/netguide/2003/feb/18crime.htm|title=Cyber crime scene in India|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, India and United States had set up an India-US cyber security forum as part of a counter-terrorism dialogue.<ref name=TOIIUC>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/1435785.cms India-US to counter cyber crime]</ref>\n\n==Corruption and police misconduct==\n{{Main|Corruption in India}}\nCorruption is widespread in India. It is prevalent within every section and every level of the society.<ref>[http://www.pucl.org/Topics/Human-rights/2002/corruption.htm Where will corruption take India?] ''[[People's Union for Civil Liberties]]''</ref> Corruption has taken the role of a pervasive aspect of Indian politics. In India, corruption takes the form of bribes, evasion of [[Tax evasion|tax]] and [[Foreign exchange controls|exchange controls]], [[embezzlement]], etc.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Social Problems in India|last=Dr.|first=Vidyadevi Patil|publisher=Laxmi Book Publication|year=2015|isbn=|location=Maharashtra|pages=29}}</ref>\n\nDespite state prohibitions against torture and custodial misconduct by the police, [[torture]] is widespread in police custody, which is a major reason behind deaths in custody.<ref>[http://www.tribuneindia.com/2007/20070313/punjab1.htm#7 Torture main reason of death in police custody] ''[[The Tribune (Chandigarh)|The Tribune]]''</ref><ref>[http://www.ahrchk.net/statements/mainfile.php/2004statement/146/ Custodial deaths in West Bengal and India's refusal to ratify the Convention against Torture] ''[[Asian Human Rights Commission]]'' 26 February 2004</ref> The police often torture innocent people until a 'confession' is obtained to save influential and wealthy offenders.<ref>[http://www.alrc.net/pr/mainfile.php/2004pr/41/ Custodial deaths and torture in India] ''[[Asian Legal Resource Centre]]''</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> G.P. Joshi, the programme coordinator of the Indian branch of the [[Commonwealth Human Rights Initiative]] in [[New Delhi]] comments that the main issue at hand concerning police violence is a lack of accountability of the police.<ref name=HRS>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hrsolidarity.net/mainfile.php/2005vol15no05/2448/ |title=Police Accountability in India: Policing Contaminated by Politics |access-date=2 February 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101224192518/http://www.hrsolidarity.net/mainfile.php/2005vol15no05/2448/ |archive-date=24 December 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, the [[Supreme Court of India]] in a judgment in the ''[[Indian Police Service#1996-2006 Reforms ordered by the Supreme Court|Prakash Singh vs. Union of India]]'' case, ordered central and state governments with seven directives to begin the process of police reform. The main objectives of this set of directives was twofold, providing tenure to and streamlining the appointment/transfer processes of policemen, and increasing the accountability of the police.<ref name=\"CSRI\">[http://www.humanrightsinitiative.org/programs/aj/police/india/initiatives/writ_petition.htm The Supreme Court takes the lead on police reform: Prakash Singh vs. Union of India], CHRI</ref>\n\nIn 2006, seven policemen were charge sheeted and eleven were convicted<ref name=NCRBSNAPSHOTS2006>[http://ncrb.nic.in/cii2006/cii-2006/Snapshots.pdf Snapshots \u2013 2006]{{Dead link|date=November 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} ''[[National Crime Records Bureau]]''</ref> for custodial misconduct. [[Jan Lokpal Bill]] is being planned to reduce the corruption.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/mumbai-to-join-hazares-fast-today-for-jan-lokpal/771505/|title=Mumbai to join Hazare's fast today for Jan Lokpal|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Other crimes==\n===Petty crime===\nPetty crime, like [[pickpocketing]], theft of valuables from luggage on trains and buses have been reported. Travelers who are not in groups become easy victims of pickpockets and purse snatchers. Purse snatchers work in crowded areas.<ref name=\"REPORT \">{{cite web|url=https://www.osac.gov/Reports/report.cfm?contentID=62882|title=Crime & Safety Report: Chennai}}</ref>\n\n===Confidence tricks===\nMany scams are perpetrated against foreign travellers, especially in [[Jaipur]], the capital of [[Rajasthan]].<ref name=\"TRAVEL \">{{cite web|url=https://www.osac.gov/Reports/report.cfm?contentID=62883|title=India 2007 Crime & Safety Report: New Delhi}}</ref> Scammers usually target younger foreign tourists and suggest to them that money can be made by privately transporting gems or gold, or by taking delivery abroad of expensive carpets, avoiding customs duties.<ref name=\"TRAVEL \"/>\n\nSuch incidents occupy the traveller for several days. The traveller is then passed to a new scam artist who offers to show the foreign traveller the sights. Scam artists also offer cheap lodgings and meals to foreign travellers so they can place him or her in the scam artist's physical custody and thus make the foreigner vulnerable to threats and physical coercion. In the process, the foreigner loses his passport.<ref name=\"TRAVEL \"/>\n\nBesides these, there are also unofficial guides to watch out for. They can be found all over India such as at crowded transportation hubs and at tourist attractions. A common ruse at transportation hubs is to claim that there is no train to your destination or to claim that a place is closed. The aim is to get you to take their expensive private transport or to an expensive hotel where they get a cut. As for the guides at tourist attractions, these could be temples, mosques, or places such as the Varanasi Ghat. You will end up receiving unsolicited services and then asked to pay a big tip for them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://travelscams.org/asia/india/|title=42 Tourist targeted scams in India|website=Travelscams.org|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-04}}</ref>\n\n===Taxi scam===\nThere are also taxi scams present in India, whereby a foreign traveller, who is not aware of the locations around Indian airports, is taken for a ride round the whole airport and charged for full-fare taxi ride while the terminal is only few hundred yards away.<ref name=\"REPORT \"/> Overseas Security Advisory Council in a report mentioned the process about how to avoid taxi-scam.  This crime is known in other areas of the world as \"long-hauling\".<ref name=\"REPORT \"/>\n\n==Preventing crimes==\nCrime prevention is critical to maintain law and order in the country. Deterring criminals through deployment of more police is one of the major strategy practised. However, their relationship is very complex. There are also other reasons such as unemployment, poverty, a lower per capita income which can affect the crime rates in India.<ref>https://bprd.nic.in/WriteReadData/userfiles/file/202001020542373723554IndianPoliceJournal.pdf |page=15</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|India|Law}}\n*[[Law enforcement in India]]\n*[[Crime and Criminal Tracking Network and Systems]]\n*[[Indian Penal Code]]\n*[[Indian mafia]]\n*[[Indian political scandals]]\n*[[Kala Kaccha Gang]]\n*[[Mafia Raj]]\n*[[Caste-related violence in India]]\n*[[Religious violence in India]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{Citation\n | last1=Edwardes\n | first1=S M\n | authorlink=\n | year=2007\n | title=Crime in India\n | place=\n | publisher=READ BOOKS\n | isbn=978-1-4067-6126-9\n | url=\n }}.\n*{{Citation\n | last1=Broadhurst\n | first1=Roderic G.\n | last2=Grabosky\n | first2=Peter N.\n | authorlink=\n | year=2005\n | title=Cyber-Crime: The Challenge in Asia\n | place=\n | publisher=[[Hong Kong University Press]]\n | isbn=962-209-724-3\n | url=\n }}.\n*{{Citation\n | last1=Menon\n | first1=Vivek\n | authorlink=\n | year=1996\n | title=Under Siege: Poaching and Protection of Greater One-Horned Rhinoceroses in India\n | place=\n | publisher=TRAFFIC International\n | isbn=1-85850-102-4\n | url=\n }}.\n*{{Citation\n | last1=Vittal\n | first1=N.\n | authorlink=\n | year=2003\n | title=Corruption in India: The Roadblock to National Prosperity\n | place=\n | publisher=Academic Foundation\n | isbn=81-7188-287-0\n | url=\n }}.\n*{{Citation\n | last1=Gupta\n | first1=K. N.\n | authorlink=\n | year=2001\n | title=Corruption in India\n | place=\n | publisher=Anmol Publications Pvt Ltd\n | isbn=81-261-0973-4\n | url=\n }}.\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://ncrb.nic.in/ National Crime Records Bureau]\n* [http://www.crimeindelhi.com/category/help-to-you/ Helpline numbers by Crime in Delhi] \n*http://indianexpress.com/article/explained/ncrb-data-uttar-pradesh-crime-rate-up-police-3033360/\n* [http://ncrb.gov.in/CII2010/home.htm Crime in India \u2013 2010] statistics\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140104213453/http://www.shareacafe.com/crime-rates-in-indian-state-wise/ Crime rates in India] State Wise\n* [http://www.hindu.com/2008/01/19/stories/2008011956120300.htm New trends in drug trafficking]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080317000845/http://www.newindpress.com/NewsItems.asp?ID=IE920080125141553&Title=Chennai&rLink=0 India becoming hot bed for drug trafficking: Expert]\n* [http://indiacrime.com/story002.html Mumbai mafia is using more sophisticated weapons than police]\n* [https://www.peoplenotpoaching.org/ People Not Poaching: The Communities and IWT Learning Platform]\n{{Social issues in India}}\n{{Crime in Asia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crime In India}}\n[[Category:Crime in India| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Indian English|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}Salem is the major cities of gang war and mafia\n\n[[File:Delhi Police Jeeps.jpg|thumb|right|Police vehicles in New Delhi]]\n\n==Crime over time==\n[[File:Crime in India from 1953 to 2007.png|thumb|500px|right|alt=India Is Criminal Justice Law System. Crime in India from 1953 to 2007|Incidence of cognisable crimes in India 1953\u20132007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ncrb.nic.in/cii2007/cii-2007/1953-2007.pdf|title=Incidence of cognizable crimes (IPC) under different crime heads during 1953\u20132007|publisher=National Crime Records Bureau|accessdate=2009-11-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090619063832/http://ncrb.nic.in/CII2007/cii-2007/1953-2007.pdf|archive-date=19 June 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n]]\nA report published by the [[National Crime Records Bureau]] compared the crime rates of 1953 and 2006. The report noted that burglary (known as house-breaking<ref name=kanoon>{{cite web|title=Central Government Act Section 445 in The Indian Penal Code|url=http://indiankanoon.org/doc/508356/|website=Indiankanoon.org|accessdate=16 July 2015}}</ref> in India) declined over a period of 53 years by 79.84% (from 147,379, a rate of 39.3/100,000 in 1953 to 91,666, a rate of 7.9/100,000 in 2006), murder has increased by 7.39% (from 9,803, a rate of 2.61 in 1953 to 32,481, a rate of 2.81/100,000 in 2006).<ref name=\"NCRBSNAPSHOTS1953-2006\">[http://ncrb.nic.in/cii2006/cii-2006/Snapshots%201953-2006.pdf Snapshots (1953\u20142006)]{{Dead link|date=November 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} ''National Crime Records Bureau''</ref>\n\n[[Kidnapping]] has increased by 47.80% (from 5,261, a rate of 1.40/100,000 in 1953 to 23,991, a rate of 2.07/100,000 in 2006), robbery has declined by 28.85% (from 8,407, rate of 2.24/100,000 in 1953 to 18,456, rate of 1.59/100,000 in 2006) and [[riots]] have declined by 10.58% (from 20,529, a rate of 5.47/100,000 in 1953 to 56,641, a rate of 4.90/100,000 in 2006).<ref name=\"NCRBSNAPSHOTS1953-2006\"/>\n\nIn 2006, {{formatnum:5102460}} cognisable crimes were committed including {{formatnum:1878293}} [[Indian Penal Code]] (IPC) crimes and {{formatnum:3224167}} Special & Local Laws (SLL) crimes, with an increase of 1.5% over 2005 (50,26,337).<ref name=NCRBSNAPSHOTS2006/> IPC crime rate in 2006 was 167.7 compared to 165.3 in 2005 showing an increase of 1.5% in 2006 over 2005.<ref name=NCRBSNAPSHOTS2006/> SLL crime rate in 2006 was 287.9 compared to 290.5 in 2005 showing a decline of 0.9% in 2006 over 2005.<ref name=NCRBSNAPSHOTS2006/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; margin-right:60px\"\n!Year<ref name=\"NCRBSNAPSHOTS1953-2006\"/>\n!Total cog. crimes under IPC, per 100,000\n!Murder per 100,000\n!Kidnapping per 100,000\n!Robbery per 100,000\n!Burglary (known as house-breaking in India) per 100,000\n|-\n|'''1953'''||160.5||2.61||1.40||2.24||39.3||\n|-\n|'''2006'''||162.3||2.81||2.07||1.60||7.92||\n|-\n|'''% Change in 2006 over 1953'''||1.1||7.39||47.80||-28.85||-79.84||\n|}\n\n'''SOURCE: National Crime Records Bureau<ref name=\"NCRBSNAPSHOTS1953-2006\"/>'''\n\n==Crime by location==\nLocation has a significant impact on crime in India. In 2012, [[Uttar Pradesh]] reported the highest cognisable crime rate of 455.8 among [[States and territories of India|States]] of [[India]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ncrb.nic.in/CD-CII2012/Statistics2012.pdf |title=Crime in India, 2012 |publisher=NCRB, Government of India |page=200 |year=2012 |accessdate=April 20, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140620023952/http://ncrb.nic.in/CD-CII2012/Statistics2012.pdf |archivedate=20 June 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/crime-rate-highest-in-kerala/article4822947.ece | title=Crime rate highest in Kerala | newspaper=The Hindu | accessdate=April 20, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Kerala-is-countrys-most-crime-prone-state-NCRB-statistics-show/articleshow/14364473.cms | title=Kerala is country's most crime-prone state, NCRB statistics show | newspaper=Times of India | accessdate=April 20, 2014}}</ref> while [[Nagaland]] recorded lowest rates (47.7). The rates were calculated by [[National Crime Records Bureau]] as the number of incidents per 100,000 of the population.\n\nIn 2006, the highest crime rate was reported in [[Puducherry]] (447.7) for crimes under [[Indian Penal Code]] which is 2.7 times the national crime rate of 167.7.<ref name=NCRBSNAPSHOTS2006/> [[Kerala]] reported the highest crime rate at 312.5 amongst all the states of India.<ref name=NCRBSNAPSHOTS2006/> \n[[Kolkata]] (71.0) the only mega city and [[Madurai]] (206.2) were the only Metropolis which reported less crime rate than their domain states [[West Bengal]] (79.0) and [[Tamil Nadu]] (227.6).<ref name=NCRBSNAPSHOTS2006/> [[Delhi]], [[Mumbai]] and [[Bangalore]] have accounted for 16.2%, 9.5% and 8.1% respectively of the total IPC crimes reported from 35 mega cities.<ref name=NCRBSNAPSHOTS2006/> [[Indore]] reported the highest crime rate (769.1) among the mega cities in India followed by [[Bhopal]] (719.5) and [[Jaipur]] (597.1).<ref name=NCRBSNAPSHOTS2006/>\n\n[[Jammu and Kashmir]] (33.7%), [[Manipur]] (33.0%), [[Assam]] (30.4%) and [[Daman and Diu]] and [[Puducherry]] (29.4%) reported higher violent crime rate compared to 18.4% at national level.<ref name=NCRBSNAPSHOTS2006/> [[Uttar Pradesh]] reported the highest incidence of violent crimes accounting for 12.1% of total violent crimes in India (40,613 out of 3,305,901) followed by [[Maharashtra]] with 11.1% (30,290 out of 3,305,901).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ncrb.gov.in/StatPublications/CII/CII2015/FILES/Snapshots-11.11.16.pdf |title=Snapshots 2015|work=[[National Crime Records Bureau]] |accessdate=18 December 2016}}</ref> Among 35 mega cities, [[Delhi]] reported 31.2% (533 out of 1,706) of total rape cases.<ref name=NCRBSNAPSHOTS2006/> [[Madhya Pradesh]] has reported the highest number of rape cases (2,900) accounting for 15.0%  of total such cases reported in the country.<ref name=NCRBSNAPSHOTS2006/> Uttar Pradesh reported 10% (5,480 out of 32,481) of total murder cases in the country and 18.4% (4,997 out of 27,230)    total attempt to murder cases.<ref name=NCRBSNAPSHOTS2006/>\n\n{{Asof|2016}} [[Uttar Pradesh]] had a lower crime rate when solely considering crimes punished under the IPC, but because of the large number of offences being prosecuted under its local laws and special laws, its overall crime rate, 1,293, is ten times the size of its IPC crime rate.<ref>{{cite news|author=Tiwary, Deepman|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/explained/ncrb-data-uttar-pradesh-crime-rate-up-police-3033360/|title=NCRB data: The odd case of crime in Uttar Pradesh, IPC rate very low, overall very high|newspaper=[[Indian Express]]|date=2016-09-26|accessdate=2017-02-14}}</ref>{{irrelevant citation|date=July 2017|reason=Opinion based, irrelevant article referenced.}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! State/UT !! 2011 !! 2012\n|-\n|India || || 2.8\n|-\n|[[Bihar]]  || 3.3 || 3.2\n|-\n| [[Arunachal Pradesh]] || 4.7 || 5.8\n|-\n| [[Assam]] || 4.2 || 4.4\n|-\n| [[Andhra Pradesh]] || 3.1 || 3.6\n|-\n| [[Chhattisgarh]] || 4.3 || 4.0\n|-\n| [[Goa]] || 3.3 || 2.5\n|-\n| [[Gujarat]] || 1.9 || 1.9\n|-\n| [[Haryana]] || 4.2 || 3.8\n|-\n| [[Himachal Pradesh]] || 1.9 || 1.6\n|-\n| [[Jammu & Kashmir]] || 1.3 || 1.0\n|-\n| [[Jharkhand]]|| 5.3 || 5.3\n|-\n| [[Karnataka]] || 3.0 || 3.1\n|-\n| [[Delhi]] || 1.1 || 1.1\n|-\n| [[Madhya Pradesh]] || 3.5 || 3.2\n|-\n| [[Maharashtra]] || 2.5 || 2.4\n|-\n| [[Manipur]] || 2.9 || 3.3\n|-\n| [[Meghalaya]] || 2.9 || 5.1\n|-\n| [[Mizoram]] || 2.4 || 2.9\n|-\n| [[Nagaland]] || 2.3 || 3.3\n|-\n| [[Odisha]] || 3.5 || 3.8\n|-\n| [[Punjab, India|Punjab]] || 3.0 || 3.0\n|-\n| [[Rajasthan]] || 2.1 || 2.1\n|-\n| [[Sikkim]] || 2.3 || 1.1\n|-\n| [[Tamil Nadu]] || 2.6 || 2.9\n|-\n| [[Tripura]] || 4.4 || 3.4\n|-\n| [[Uttar Pradesh]] || 7.5 || 7.4\n|-\n| [[Uttarakhand]] || 1.8 || 2.1\n|-\n| [[West Bengal]]  || 2.3 || 2.5\n|-\n| [[Kerala]] || 10 || 5\n\n|}\n\nSources.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ncrb.nic.in/CD-CII2011/cii-2011/Table%203.1.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-09-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130928024506/http://ncrb.nic.in/CD-CII2011/cii-2011/Table%203.1.pdf |archivedate=28 September 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>[[List of states and union territories of India by population]]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ncrb.nic.in/CD-CII2012/Statistics2012.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=20 April 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140620023952/http://ncrb.nic.in/CD-CII2012/Statistics2012.pdf |archivedate=20 June 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Crimes against women==\n{{Main|Violence against women in India}}\n\nPolice records shows incidence of crimes against women in India.<ref name=\"un_women_free_equal\">{{cite web\n |title=Women in India: How Free? How Equal? \n |url=http://www.un.org.in/wii.htm \n |author=Kalyani Menon-Sen, [[A. K. Shiva Kumar]] \n |publisher=United Nations \n |year=2001 \n |accessdate=2006-12-24 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060911183722/http://www.un.org.in/wii.htm \n |archivedate=11 September 2006 \n |url-status=dead \n |df=dmy \n}}</ref> Sexual assault against women in India though not common is present. Despite a large population statistically sexual assault in India is not rampant. Media is active in highlighting cases of Sexual assault against women.<ref name=\"un_women_free_equal\"/>\n\n===Rape===\n{{Main|Rape in India}}\nRape in India has been described by [[Radha Kumar]] as one of India's most common crimes against women.<ref name=Kumar>{{cite book|last=Kumar|first=Radha|title=The History of Doing: An Account of Women's Rights and Feminism in India|year=1993|publisher=Zubaan|isbn=978-8185107769|page=128}}</ref> Official sources show that rape cases in India have doubled between 1990 and 2008<ref name=AFP>{{cite web|title=www.arabnews.com/indian-student-gang-raped-thrown-bus-new-delhi|publisher=AFP|date=17 December 2012}}</ref> In most of the rape cases, the culprit is known to the victim.\n\nAccording to [[National Crime Records Bureau]] data of 2012,<ref name=\"Crime2012\">{{cite web|url=http://ncrb.nic.in/CD-CII2012/Statistics2012.pdf |title=Crime in India, 2012 |publisher=NCRB, Government of India |page=206 |year=2012 |accessdate=April 20, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140620023952/http://ncrb.nic.in/CD-CII2012/Statistics2012.pdf |archivedate=20 June 2014 }}</ref> [[Gujarat]] has the lowest rape rate (0.8) while [[Mizoram]] had the highest rape rate with a value of 10.1. the National Average was at 2.1. The rates were calculated by [[National Crime Records Bureau]] as the number of incidents per 100,000 of the population\n\n===Dowry===\n{{Main|Dowry system in India}}\n\n[[Dowries]] are considered a major contributor towards [[violence against women in India]].  Some of these offences include physical violence, emotional abuses, and murder of brides and girls.<ref name=\"srinivasan 2004\">{{cite journal|last=Srinivasan|first=Padma|author2=Gary R. Lee|title=The Dowry System in Northern India: Women's Attitudes and Social Change|journal=Journal of Marriage and Family|year=2004|volume=66|issue=5|pages=1108\u20131117|doi=10.1111/j.0022-2445.2004.00081.x}}</ref><ref name=\"Teays 1991\">{{cite journal|last=Teays|first=Wanda|title=The Burning Bride: The Dowry Problem in India|journal=Journal of Feminist Studies in Religion|year=1991|volume=7|issue=2|pages=29\u201352}}</ref><ref name=\"Bloch 2002\">{{cite journal|last=Bloch|first=Francis|author2=Vijayendra Rao|title=Terror as a Bargaining Instrument: A Case Study of Dowry Violence in Rural India|journal=The American Economic Review|year=2002|volume=92|issue=4|pages=1029\u20131043|doi=10.1257/00028280260344588|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/beeabaff4f09cafdc47e08adb378db3f360bec10}}</ref>\n\nMost dowry deaths occur when the young woman, unable to bear the harassment and torture, commits suicide. Most of these suicides are by hanging, poisoning or by fire. Sometimes the woman is killed by setting her on fire - this is known as [[bride burning]], and is sometimes disguised as suicide or accident.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Kumar|first=Virendra|title=Burnt wives|journal=Burns|date=Feb 2003|volume=29|issue=1|pages=31\u201336|doi=10.1016/s0305-4179(02)00235-8|pmid=12543042}}</ref> In 2012, 8,233 dowry death cases were reported across India.<ref name=india>{{cite web|url=http://ncrb.nic.in/CD-CII2012/Statistics2012.pdf |title=National Crime Statistics (page 196) |publisher=National Crime Records Bureau, India |date=2013-01-16 |accessdate=2015-01-02 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140620023952/http://ncrb.nic.in/CD-CII2012/Statistics2012.pdf |archivedate=20 June 2014 }}</ref> Dowry issues caused 1.4 deaths per year per 100,000 women in India.<ref>[http://censusindia.gov.in/2011census/censusinfodashboard/index.html Provisional 2011 Census Data], Government of India (2011)</ref><ref name=crimeindia2011>[http://ncrb.nic.in/CD-CII2011/Statistics2011.pdf Crime statistics in India] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130129164006/http://ncrb.nic.in/CD-CII2011/Statistics2011.pdf |date=29 January 2013 }}, Government of India (2011)</ref>\n\n===Domestic violence===\n{{Further|Domestic violence in India}}\n\n[[Domestic violence in India]] is endemic.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Ganguly|first=Sumit|title=India's Shame|url=http://the-diplomat.com/indian-decade/2012/04/14/india%E2%80%99s-shame/|magazine=The Diplomat|accessdate=27 April 2012}}</ref> Around 70% of women in India are victims of domestic violence, according to [[Renuka Chowdhury]], former Union minister for Women and Child Development.<ref name=\"Chowdhury 2006\">{{cite news|last=Chowdhury|first=Renuka|title=India tackles domestic violence|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/6086334.stm|newspaper=BBC|date=26 October 2006}}</ref>\n\nThe National Crime Records Bureau reveal that a crime against a woman is committed every three minutes, a woman is raped every 29 minutes, a [[dowry]] death occurs every 77 minutes, and one case of cruelty committed by either the husband or relative of the husband occurs every nine minutes.<ref name=\"bbctackle\"/> This occurs despite the fact that women in India are legally protected from domestic abuse under the [[Protection of Women from Domestic Violence Act 2005|Protection of Women from Domestic Violence Act]].<ref name=\"bbctackle\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/6086334.stm|title=India tackles domestic violence|date=2006-10-27|work=BBC News|accessdate=25 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Organised crime ==\n{{Further|Organised crime in India}}\n\n===Illegal drug trade===\nIndia is located between two major illicit [[opium]] producing centres in Asia \u2013 the [[Golden Crescent]] comprising [[Pakistan]], [[Afghanistan]] and [[Iran]] and the [[Golden Triangle (Southeast Asia)|Golden Triangle]] comprising [[Burma]], Thailand and [[Laos]].<ref name=\"PINM658\">{{cite book\n|author= P. J. Alexander\n|title= Policing India in the New Millennium\n|publisher= Allied Publishers\n|location=\n|year= 2002\n|pages= 658\n|isbn= 81-7764-207-3\n|oclc=\n|doi=\n}}</ref> Because of such geographical location, India experiences large amount of drug trafficking through the borders.<ref name=\"IDPTU183\">{{cite book\n|author1=Caterina Gouvis Roman |author2=Heather Ahn-Redding |author3=Rita James Simon |title= Illicit Drug Policies, Trafficking, and Use the World Over\n|publisher= Lexington Books\n|location=\n|year= 2007\n|pages= 183\n|isbn= 978-0-7391-2088-0\n|oclc=\n|doi=\n}}</ref> India is the world's largest producer of licit opium for the pharmaceutical trade.<ref name=\" CIA World Factbook\">{{cite web |title=CIA World Factbook \u2013 India|work=[[CIA World Factbook]]|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/in.html |accessdate=2007-12-01}}</ref> But an undetermined quantity of opium is diverted to illicit international drug markets.<ref name=\" CIA World Factbook\"/>\n\nIndia is a transshipment point for heroin from [[Southwest Asian]] countries like [[Afghanistan]] and [[Pakistan]] and from Southeast Asian countries like Burma, Laos, and Thailand.<ref name=SDSU>{{cite web|url=http://www-rohan.sdsu.edu/faculty/rwinslow/asia_pacific/india.html|title=Comparative Criminology - Asia - India|publisher=}}</ref> Heroin is smuggled from [[Pakistan]] and Burma, with some quantities transshipped through Nepal.<ref name=SDSU/> Most heroin shipped from India are destined for Europe.<ref name=SDSU/> There have been reports of heroin smuggled from [[Mumbai]] to [[Nigeria]] for further export.<ref name=SDSU/>\n\nIn [[Maharashtra]], [[Mumbai]] is an important centre for distribution of drug.<ref name=\" Molly Charles\">{{cite web |title=Drug trade dynamics in India|url=http://laniel.free.fr/INDEXES/PapersIndex/INDIAMOLLY/DRUGSDYNAMICSININDIA.htm}}</ref> The most commonly used drug in Mumbai is Indian heroin (called ''desi mal'' by the local population).<ref name=\" Molly Charles\"/> Both public transportation (road and rail transportation) and private transportation are used for this drug trade.<ref name=\" Molly Charles\"/>\n\nDrug trafficking affects the country in many ways.\n*[[Drug abuse]]: Cultivation of illicit narcotic substances and drug trafficking affects the health of the individuals and destroy the economic structure of the family and society.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thishour.in/112/if-you-think-drugs-will-make-you-high-watch-this|title=Life of Drug Addicts: Curtains Down|last=|first=|date=|website=www.thishour.in|publisher=THISHOUR.in|access-date=2016-10-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160918221439/http://www.thishour.in/112/if-you-think-drugs-will-make-you-high-watch-this|archive-date=18 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"PINM659\">{{cite book\n|author= P. J. Alexander\n|title= Policing India in the New Millennium\n|publisher= Allied Publishers\n|location=\n|year= 2002\n|pages= 659\n|isbn= 81-7764-207-3\n|oclc=\n|doi=\n}}</ref>\n*[[Organised crime]]: Drug trafficking results in growth of organised crime which affects [[social security]]. Organised crime connects drug trafficking with corruption and [[money laundering]].<ref name=\"PINM659\"/>\n*Political instability: Drug trafficking also aggravates the political instability in [[North-West India|North-West]] and [[North-East India]].<ref name=\"WGD53\">{{cite book\n|author1=Alain Labrousse |author2=Laurent Laniel |title= The World Geopolitics of Drugs, 1998/1999\n|publisher= Springer\n|location=\n|year= 2002\n|pages= 53\n|isbn= 1-4020-0140-1\n|oclc=\n|doi=\n}}</ref>\n\nA survey conducted in 2003\u20132004 by Narcotics Control Bureau found that India has at least four million drug addicts.<ref name=\" NCB\">{{cite web|title=Mechanism in States|url=http://narcoticsindia.nic.in/Mechinstates.htm}}</ref> The most common drugs used in India are [[Cannabis (drug)|cannabis]], [[hashish]], [[opium]] and heroin.<ref name=\" NCB\"/> In 2006 alone, India's law enforcing agencies recovered 230&nbsp;kg heroin and 203&nbsp;kg of [[cocaine]].<ref name=TOIAIRPORT>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/1680312.cms Airports get scanners to check drug trafficking]</ref> In an annual government report in 2007, the United States named India among 20 major hubs for trafficking of illegal drugs along with Pakistan, Afghanistan and Burma. However, studies reveal that most of the criminals caught in this crime are either Nigerian or [[United States|US]] nationals.<ref name=\" Hindustan\">{{cite web |title=US names India among 20 major hubs for drug trafficking|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/StoryPage/StoryPage.aspx?id=5f7ed0c7-60a5-40fc-bbf1-7e9b4c070f59&&Headline=India+among+20+major+drug+hubs%3a+US}}</ref>\n\nSeveral measures have been taken by the [[Government of India]] to combat drug trafficking in the country. India is a party of the [[Single Convention on Narcotic Drugs]] (1961), the [[Convention on Psychotropic Substances]] (1971), the [[Protocol Amending the Single Convention on Narcotic Drugs]] (1972) and the [[United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances]] (1988).<ref name=\"IPCAWP172\">{{cite book\n|author= Daniel J. Koenig\n|title= International Police Cooperation: A World Perspective\n|publisher= Lexington Books\n|location=\n|year= 2001\n|pages= 172\n|isbn= 0-7391-0226-5\n|oclc=\n|doi=\n}}</ref> An Indo-Pakistani committee was set up in 1986 to prevent trafficking in narcotic drugs.<ref name=\"IPCAWP173\">{{cite book\n|author= Daniel J. Koenig\n|title= International Police Cooperation: A World Perspective\n|publisher= Lexington Books\n|location=\n|year= 2001\n|pages= 173\n|isbn= 0-7391-0226-5\n|oclc=\n|doi=\n}}</ref> India signed a convention with the [[United Arab Emirates]] in 1994 to control drug trafficking.<ref name=\"IPCAWP173\"/> In 1995, India signed an agreement with [[Egypt]] for investigation of drug cases and exchange of information and a [[Memorandum of understanding|Memorandum of Understanding]] of the Prevention of Illicit Trafficking in Drugs with [[Iran]].<ref name=\"IPCAWP173\"/>\n\n===Arms trafficking===\nAccording to a joint report published by [[Oxfam]], [[Amnesty International]] and the [[IANSA (NGO)|International Action Network on Small Arms]] (IANSA) in 2006, there are around 40 million illegal small arms in India out of approximately 75 million in worldwide circulation.<ref name=DTILLEGALARMS>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2006%5C04%5C02%5Cstory_2-4-2006_pg7_11|title=DailyTimes - Your Right To Know|work=DAILYTIMES}}</ref> Majority of the illegal small arms make its way into the states of [[Bihar]], [[Chhattisgarh]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], Jharkhand, [[Orissa, India|Orissa]] and [[Madhya Pradesh]].<ref name=DTILLEGALARMS/> In UP, a used [[AK-47]] costs $3,800 in black market.<ref name=\"HAVOCSCOPE\">{{cite web |title=Small Arms Trafficking|url=http://www.havocscope.com/trafficking/smallarms.htm}}</ref> Large amount of illegal small arms are manufactured in various illegal arms factories in Uttar Pradesh and Bihar and sold on the black market for as little as $5.08.<ref name=DTILLEGALARMS/>\n\nChinese pistols are in demand in the illegal small arms market in India because they are easily available and cheaper.<ref name=DTILLEGALARMS/> This trend poses a significant problem for the states of [[Bihar]], Uttar Pradesh, Jharkhand, Chhattisgarh, Orissa, Maharashtra, [[West Bengal]], Karnataka and [[Andhra Pradesh]] which have influence of [[Naxalism]].<ref name=DTILLEGALARMS/> The porous Indo-Nepal border is an entry point for Chinese pistols, AK-47 and [[M16 rifle|M-16 rifles]] into India as these arms are used by the Naxalites who have ties to Maoists in Nepal.<ref name=DTILLEGALARMS/>\n\nIn [[North-East India]], there is a huge influx of small arms due to the insurgent groups operating there.<ref name=GWDDSA>[http://www.peacebuild.ca/action/res/Bina%20Nepram%20lecture,%2022%20March,%202004,%20Ottawa.doc A Narrative of Armed Ethnic Conflict, Narcotics and Small Arms Trafficking in India's North East]</ref> The small arms in North-East India come from insurgent groups in Burma, black markets in [[Southeast Asia]], [[Pakistan]], Bangladesh, [[Nepal]] and [[Sri Lanka]], black market in [[Cambodia]], the People's Republic of China, insurgent groups like the [[Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam]], the [[Communist Party of India (Maoist)]], the [[Communist Party of Nepal (Maoist)]], Indian states like [[Uttar Pradesh]] and pilferages from legal gun factories,\ncriminal organisations operating in India and South Asian countries and\nother international markets like [[Romania]], Germany etc.<ref name=GWDDSA/> Illegal weaponry found in North-East India includes small arms such as the [[M14 rifle|M14]], [[M16 rifle|M16]], [[AK-47]], [[AK-56]], and the [[AK-74]], but also [[light machine gun]]s, Chinese [[hand grenade]]s, [[Land mine|mines]], [[rocket-propelled grenade|rocket-propelled grenade launchers]] and [[submachine gun]]s etc.<ref name=GWDDSA/>\n\nThe [[Ministry of External Affairs (India)|Ministry of External Affairs]] and [[Ministry of Home Affairs (India)|Ministry of Home Affairs]] drafted a joint proposal to the United Nations, seeking a global ban on small-arms sales to non-state users.<ref name=DTILLEGALARMS/>\n\n==Poaching and wildlife trafficking==\nIllegal wildlife trade in India has increased.<ref name=REUTERSPOACHING>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/environmentNews/idUSDEL8332720070817?sp=true|title=Illegal wildlife trade grows in India|author=Reuters Editorial|date=17 August 2007|work=Reuters}}</ref> According to a report published by the [[Environmental Investigation Agency]] (EIA) in 2004, India is the chief target for the traders of wildlife skin.<ref name=EIATTST>[http://www.eia-international.org/files/reports85-1.pdf The Tiger Skin Trail] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012162946/http://www.eia-international.org/files/reports85-1.pdf |date=12 October 2007 }}</ref> Between 1994 and 2003, there have been 784 cases where the skins of tiger, leopard or [[otter]] have been seized.<ref name=EIATTST/> [[Leopard]]s, [[rhinoceros]], [[reptile]]s, birds, insects, rare species of plants are being smuggled into the countries in Southeast Asia and the People's Republic of China.<ref name=REUTERSPOACHING/> Between 1994 and 2003, poaching and seizure of 698 otters have been documented in India.<ref name=EIATTST/>\n\n[[Kathmandu]] is a key staging point for illegal skins smuggled from India bound for [[Tibet]] and PRC.<ref name=EIATTST/> The report by EIA noted there has been a lack of cross-border cooperation between India, [[Nepal]] and the People's Republic of [[China]] to coordinate enforcement operations and lack of political will to treat wildlife crime effectively.<ref name=EIATTST/> The poaching of the [[Asian Elephant|elephants]] is a significant problem in Southern India<ref name=\"AEEM210\">{{cite book\n|author= R. Sukumar\n|title= The Asian Elephant: Ecology and Management\n|publisher= Cambridge University Press\n|location=\n|year= 1989\n|pages= 210\n|isbn= 0-521-43758-X\n|oclc=\n|doi=\n}}</ref> and in the North-Eastern states of [[Nagaland]] and [[Mizoram]].<ref name=\"AEC30\">{{cite book\n|author1=Charles Santiapillai |author2=Peter Jackson |title= The Asian Elephant: An Action Plan for Its Conservation\n|publisher=\n|location=\n|year= 1990\n|pages= 30\n|isbn= 2-88032-997-3\n|oclc=\n|doi=\n}}</ref> The majority of tiger poaching happen in [[Madhya Pradesh]], Uttar Pradesh, [[Orissa, India|Orissa]], West Bengal, [[Assam]] and [[Arunachal Pradesh]].<ref name=IYT>[http://www.internatyearofthetiger.org/india.htm The situation in India]</ref> Following is a comparison of reported cases of tiger and leopard poaching from 1998 to 2003:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; margin-right:60px\"\n!Year\n!1998\n!1999\n!2000\n!2001\n!2002\n!2003\n|-\n|'''Reported cases of tiger poaching<ref name=PTPS>[http://projecttiger.nic.in/poaching.asp# Poaching & Seizure Cases]</ref>'''||14||38||39||35||47||8\n|-\n|'''Reported cases of leopard poaching<ref name=PTPS/>'''||28||80||201||69||87||15\n|}\n\nSamir Sinha, head of [[Traffic (conservation programme)|TRAFFIC India]], the wildlife trade monitoring arm of the [[World Wide Fund for Nature]] (WWF) and the [[World Conservation Union]] (IUCN), told [[Reuters]] in an interview \"The situation regarding the illegal trade in wildlife parts in India is very grim. It is a vast, a varied trade ranging from smuggling of rare medicinal plants to butterflies to peafowl to tigers and it is difficult to predict how big it is, but the threats and dimensions suggest that the trade is increasing\".<ref name=REUTERSPOACHING/>\n\n[[Project Tiger]], a wildlife conservation project, was initiated in 1972 and was launched by [[Indira Gandhi]] on 1 April 1973.<ref name=REDIFFTIGER>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/1998/oct/02tiger.htm|title=Rediff On The NeT Special: At least one tiger is killed by poachers every day|publisher=}}</ref> With 23 tiger reserves, Project Tiger claimed to have succeeded.<ref name=REDIFFTIGER/> But according to critics like conservationist Billy Arjan Singh, temporary increases in tiger population were caused by immigration due to destruction of habitat in Nepal, not because of the widely acclaimed success of wildlife policy in India.<ref name=REDIFFTIGER/>\n\n==Cyber crime==\n{{Main|Cybercrime in India}}\nThe Information Technology Act 2000 was passed by the [[Parliament of India]] in May 2000, aiming to curb cyber crimes and provide a legal framework for [[Electronic commerce|e-commerce]] transactions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/978231.stm|title=BBC News - SOUTH ASIA - India cyber law comes into force|publisher=}}</ref> However Pavan Duggal, lawyer of [[Supreme Court of India]] and cyber law expert, viewed \"The IT Act, 2000, is primarily meant to be a legislation to promote e-commerce. It is not very effective in dealing with several emerging cyber crimes like [[cyber harassment]], [[defamation]], stalking and so on\". Although cyber crime cells have been set up in major cities, Duggal noted the problem is that most cases remain unreported due to a lack of awareness.<ref name=REDIFFBB>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/netguide/2003/feb/18crime.htm|title=Cyber crime scene in India|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, India and United States had set up an India-US cyber security forum as part of a counter-terrorism dialogue.<ref name=TOIIUC>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/1435785.cms India-US to counter cyber crime]</ref>\n\n==Corruption and police misconduct==\n{{Main|Corruption in India}}\nCorruption is widespread in India. It is prevalent within every section and every level of the society.<ref>[http://www.pucl.org/Topics/Human-rights/2002/corruption.htm Where will corruption take India?] ''[[People's Union for Civil Liberties]]''</ref> Corruption has taken the role of a pervasive aspect of Indian politics. In India, corruption takes the form of bribes, evasion of [[Tax evasion|tax]] and [[Foreign exchange controls|exchange controls]], [[embezzlement]], etc.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Social Problems in India|last=Dr.|first=Vidyadevi Patil|publisher=Laxmi Book Publication|year=2015|isbn=|location=Maharashtra|pages=29}}</ref>\n\nDespite state prohibitions against torture and custodial misconduct by the police, [[torture]] is widespread in police custody, which is a major reason behind deaths in custody.<ref>[http://www.tribuneindia.com/2007/20070313/punjab1.htm#7 Torture main reason of death in police custody] ''[[The Tribune (Chandigarh)|The Tribune]]''</ref><ref>[http://www.ahrchk.net/statements/mainfile.php/2004statement/146/ Custodial deaths in West Bengal and India's refusal to ratify the Convention against Torture] ''[[Asian Human Rights Commission]]'' 26 February 2004</ref> The police often torture innocent people until a 'confession' is obtained to save influential and wealthy offenders.<ref>[http://www.alrc.net/pr/mainfile.php/2004pr/41/ Custodial deaths and torture in India] ''[[Asian Legal Resource Centre]]''</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> G.P. Joshi, the programme coordinator of the Indian branch of the [[Commonwealth Human Rights Initiative]] in [[New Delhi]] comments that the main issue at hand concerning police violence is a lack of accountability of the police.<ref name=HRS>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hrsolidarity.net/mainfile.php/2005vol15no05/2448/ |title=Police Accountability in India: Policing Contaminated by Politics |access-date=2 February 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101224192518/http://www.hrsolidarity.net/mainfile.php/2005vol15no05/2448/ |archive-date=24 December 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, the [[Supreme Court of India]] in a judgment in the ''[[Indian Police Service#1996-2006 Reforms ordered by the Supreme Court|Prakash Singh vs. Union of India]]'' case, ordered central and state governments with seven directives to begin the process of police reform. The main objectives of this set of directives was twofold, providing tenure to and streamlining the appointment/transfer processes of policemen, and increasing the accountability of the police.<ref name=\"CSRI\">[http://www.humanrightsinitiative.org/programs/aj/police/india/initiatives/writ_petition.htm The Supreme Court takes the lead on police reform: Prakash Singh vs. Union of India], CHRI</ref>\n\nIn 2006, seven policemen were charge sheeted and eleven were convicted<ref name=NCRBSNAPSHOTS2006>[http://ncrb.nic.in/cii2006/cii-2006/Snapshots.pdf Snapshots \u2013 2006]{{Dead link|date=November 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} ''[[National Crime Records Bureau]]''</ref> for custodial misconduct. [[Jan Lokpal Bill]] is being planned to reduce the corruption.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/mumbai-to-join-hazares-fast-today-for-jan-lokpal/771505/|title=Mumbai to join Hazare's fast today for Jan Lokpal|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Other crimes==\n===Petty crime===\nPetty crime, like [[pickpocketing]], theft of valuables from luggage on trains and buses have been reported. Travelers who are not in groups become easy victims of pickpockets and purse snatchers. Purse snatchers work in crowded areas.<ref name=\"REPORT \">{{cite web|url=https://www.osac.gov/Reports/report.cfm?contentID=62882|title=Crime & Safety Report: Chennai}}</ref>\n\n===Confidence tricks===\nMany scams are perpetrated against foreign travellers, especially in [[Jaipur]], the capital of [[Rajasthan]].<ref name=\"TRAVEL \">{{cite web|url=https://www.osac.gov/Reports/report.cfm?contentID=62883|title=India 2007 Crime & Safety Report: New Delhi}}</ref> Scammers usually target younger foreign tourists and suggest to them that money can be made by privately transporting gems or gold, or by taking delivery abroad of expensive carpets, avoiding customs duties.<ref name=\"TRAVEL \"/>\n\nSuch incidents occupy the traveller for several days. The traveller is then passed to a new scam artist who offers to show the foreign traveller the sights. Scam artists also offer cheap lodgings and meals to foreign travellers so they can place him or her in the scam artist's physical custody and thus make the foreigner vulnerable to threats and physical coercion. In the process, the foreigner loses his passport.<ref name=\"TRAVEL \"/>\n\nBesides these, there are also unofficial guides to watch out for. They can be found all over India such as at crowded transportation hubs and at tourist attractions. A common ruse at transportation hubs is to claim that there is no train to your destination or to claim that a place is closed. The aim is to get you to take their expensive private transport or to an expensive hotel where they get a cut. As for the guides at tourist attractions, these could be temples, mosques, or places such as the Varanasi Ghat. You will end up receiving unsolicited services and then asked to pay a big tip for them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://travelscams.org/asia/india/|title=42 Tourist targeted scams in India|website=Travelscams.org|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-04}}</ref>\n\n===Taxi scam===\nThere are also taxi scams present in India, whereby a foreign traveller, who is not aware of the locations around Indian airports, is taken for a ride round the whole airport and charged for full-fare taxi ride while the terminal is only few hundred yards away.<ref name=\"REPORT \"/> Overseas Security Advisory Council in a report mentioned the process about how to avoid taxi-scam.  This crime is known in other areas of the world as \"long-hauling\".<ref name=\"REPORT \"/>\n\n==Preventing crimes==\nCrime prevention is critical to maintain law and order in the country. Deterring criminals through deployment of more police is one of the major strategy practised. However, their relationship is very complex. There are also other reasons such as unemployment, poverty, a lower per capita income which can affect the crime rates in India.<ref>https://bprd.nic.in/WriteReadData/userfiles/file/202001020542373723554IndianPoliceJournal.pdf |page=15</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|India|Law}}\n*[[Law enforcement in India]]\n*[[Crime and Criminal Tracking Network and Systems]]\n*[[Indian Penal Code]]\n*[[Indian mafia]]\n*[[Indian political scandals]]\n*[[Kala Kaccha Gang]]\n*[[Mafia Raj]]\n*[[Caste-related violence in India]]\n*[[Religious violence in India]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{Citation\n | last1=Edwardes\n | first1=S M\n | authorlink=\n | year=2007\n | title=Crime in India\n | place=\n 